

=== Inter-Language Data Flow

When a function in one language calls a function in another, data must cross a
language boundary. Morloc handles this transparently: the caller's pool
serializes the value into a language-neutral binary form, sends a packet over a
Unix socket, and the receiver's pool deserializes it back into a native value.

This section describes how that marshalling works.

==== The marshalling pipeline

Every cross-language value transfer follows the same pipeline:

----
Sender                                          Receiver
 native value                                    native value
      |                                               ^
      v                                               |
 [toAnything]                                    [fromAnything]
      |                                               ^
      v                                               |
 voidstar (binary in shared memory)              voidstar (binary)
      |                                               ^
      v                                               |
 [make packet]                                   [read packet]
      |                                               ^
      v                                               |
 packet bytes  ---- Unix domain socket ---->  packet bytes
----

**toAnything** converts a native value (a Python dict, a C++ struct, an R list)
into the voidstar binary format -- a flat, language-neutral representation
stored in shared memory. Each language provides its own `toAnything`
implementation. The result is a block of bytes with a known layout described by
a schema string.

**fromAnything** does the reverse: given a pointer to voidstar binary data and a
schema, it reconstructs the native value in the target language.

Both directions are guided by the same **schema string** (e.g., `m2<4>namesi4<3>ageu1`
for `{name: Str, age: UInt8}`). The schema travels with the packet as metadata.


==== Two data paths: inline vs. shared memory

Not all data takes the same route between sender and receiver. Morloc chooses
between two paths based on the serialized size:

[mermaid]
....
flowchart LR
    A["native value"] --> B["toAnything\n(serialize to voidstar\nin shared memory)"]
    B --> C{"size <= 64 KB?"}
    C -- yes --> D["copy into packet\n(inline)"]
    C -- no --> E["keep in shared memory\n(send 8-byte pointer)"]
    D --> F["packet over socket"]
    E --> F
....

===== Inline path (small data)

For values that serialize to 64 KB or less -- the common case for primitives,
short strings, small records, and modest arrays -- the voidstar binary is
copied directly into the packet payload. The shared memory allocation is freed
immediately.

On the receiver side, the data is read directly from the packet buffer.
No shared memory is touched.

----
Sender pool                              Receiver pool
  native value                             native value
       |                                        ^
       v                                        |
  toAnything -> voidstar in SHM            fromAnything
       |                                        ^
       v                                        |
  flatten into packet payload    --->    read from packet payload
  free SHM immediately                   (no SHM needed)
----

This path avoids the overhead of shared memory coordination: no global mutex
for allocation, no reference counting, no cross-process cleanup. For the
many small values that flow between pools, this is a significant win.


===== Shared memory path (large data)

For values larger than 64 KB -- large arrays, genomic sequences, big matrices
-- the voidstar binary stays in shared memory. The packet carries only an
8-byte relative pointer to the data.

----
Sender pool                              Receiver pool
  native value                             native value
       |                                        ^
       v                                        |
  toAnything -> voidstar in SHM            fromAnything
       |                                        ^
       v                                        |
  send 8-byte pointer in packet  --->    resolve pointer to SHM
  track SHM for deferred cleanup         increment reference count
----

The receiver resolves the relative pointer to access the data in shared memory
directly -- no copy is needed. Reference counting ensures the memory is not
freed while any pool still holds a reference.


==== Tracing a cross-language call

Consider a Morloc program that calls a Python function from C++:

[source, morloc]
----
import root
import root-py (Str, Int, List)
import root-cpp (Str, Int, List)

source Py from "analyze.py" ("summarize")
source Cpp from "prepare.hpp" ("prepare")

summarize :: [Str] -> Str
prepare :: Int -> [Str]

pipeline n = summarize (prepare n)
----

When the user runs `./pipeline pipeline 5`, here is what happens:

[mermaid]
....
sequenceDiagram
    participant Nexus
    participant C++ Pool
    participant Python Pool
    participant SHM as Shared Memory

    Nexus->>C++ Pool: call prepare(5)
    Note over C++ Pool: prepare returns<br/>["a","bb","ccc","dddd","eeeee"]

    C++ Pool->>C++ Pool: toAnything: C++ vector<string><br/>-> voidstar binary (71 bytes)
    Note over C++ Pool: 71 bytes < 64 KB<br/>-> inline path

    C++ Pool->>Python Pool: packet with inline voidstar payload
    Note over Python Pool: fromAnything: voidstar binary<br/>-> Python list of str

    Python Pool->>Python Pool: summarize(["a","bb",...])
    Note over Python Pool: returns "a,bb,ccc,dddd,eeeee"

    Python Pool->>Python Pool: toAnything: Python str<br/>-> voidstar binary (36 bytes)
    Python Pool->>C++ Pool: packet with inline payload
    C++ Pool-->>Nexus: result packet
    Nexus->>Nexus: print "a,bb,ccc,dddd,eeeee"
....

Key points:

* The C++ and Python pools each have their own `toAnything` and `fromAnything`
  implementations, but they agree on the same voidstar binary layout because
  both are driven by the same schema.

* Because the data is small, both transfers use the inline path. No shared
  memory coordination is needed at all.

* If `prepare` returned a million strings instead of five, the serialized size
  would exceed 64 KB, and the system would automatically switch to the shared
  memory path -- no code changes required.


==== What gets serialized

Not every function call involves serialization. Morloc has three tiers of call
cost:

[cols="2, 3, 4"]
|===
| Call type | Cost | Example

| **Intra-pool** (same language)
| Near-native function call. No serialization, no socket, no IPC.
| A Python function calling another Python function within the same pool.

| **Inter-pool, small data**
| Socket round-trip + serialize/deserialize. Data travels inline in the packet.
| Passing a record with a few fields between C++ and Python.

| **Inter-pool, large data**
| Socket round-trip + serialize + shared memory bookkeeping. Only a pointer travels over the socket.
| Passing a large matrix between R and C++.
|===

The threshold between "small" and "large" is 64 KB of serialized voidstar
binary. This is the size after serialization, not the size of the native
object -- a Python list of integers may serialize to a compact array of
fixed-width values that is much smaller than the Python object.

